article.description:
Chamique Holdsclaw had 18 points and 15 rebounds Sunday to lead the Washington Mystics to a 63-45 victory
over the Cleveland Rockers.
article.headline: Mystics don't miss a beat with two starters out
article.linkText: Minus two starters, Mystics still rip Rockers
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw had 18 points and 15
rebounds Sunday to lead the Washington Mystics to a 63-45 victory
over the Cleveland Rockers.

	   The Mystics played without starters Annie Burgess (lower back
strain) and Stacy Dales-Schuman (stomach virus). They were replaced
in the lineup by guard Audrey Sauret and forward Murriel Page, who
had a season-high 15 points and six rebounds in her third start of
the season.

	   "We did not know that we were going to be faced with what we
were faced with until we walked in the door today,'' Mystics coach
Marianne Stanley said. "I was happy that we responded the way we
did. That's the sign of a really good team.''

	   Chasity Melvin led Cleveland (3-6) with 10 points and four
rebounds.

	   The Mystics opened the second half with a 7-2 run, capped by
Coco Miller's 3-pointer for a 41-26 lead with 18:05 remaining.
Asjha Jones' layup gave Washington a 51-31 lead with 10:53 left.

	   Miller scored 12 points for the Mystics (9-2), who've won six in
a row at home.

	   Holdsclaw, who shot 8-for-13 from the field, gave Washington
first-half leads of 25-13 and 30-18 with 3-pointers. Entering the
game, she had attempted only three shots from behind the arc this
season.

	   "I trail a lot,'' Holdsclaw said. "So if they're not going to
be there, I'm not gun shy. I'm going to take that shot, and today
they went in.''

	   Miller's layup gave Washington its biggest lead of the first
half, 27-14, with 5:05 remaining.

	   Rockers guard Jennifer Rizzotti was cut above her left eye when
she collided with Muriel Page's knee with 14:30 left in the second
half. She received stitches and returned late in the game to finish
with five points and three steals.
